<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="416" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="20.[113,752,1826,2106]" lastBlockId="20.[812,1452,975,1543]" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,230,1826,1850]" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Carapace subquadrate, about 1.6 times as broad as long, dorsal surface very smooth, region indistinct, median H-shaped depression shallow; some small granules present on dorsolateral margins, only scattered tiny granules on posterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[370,482,1954,1978]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="21.[136,171,2062,2084]" captionTargetBox="[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetId="figure-40@21.[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Fig. 16. Hexapinus latus, new species, holotype female (8.1 × 5.0 mm) (MZB Cru 3918). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353977/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">Fig. 16A</figureCitation>
). Anterolateral margin arcuate, posterolateral margin sinuous with 1 protuberance; posterolateral corner with angled prominence over base of posterior pereopods; lateral margin of carapace wall produced medially. Front deflexed (
<figureCitation box="[490,587,2082,2106]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="21.[136,171,2062,2084]" captionTargetBox="[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetId="figure-40@21.[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Fig. 16. Hexapinus latus, new species, holotype female (8.1 × 5.0 mm) (MZB Cru 3918). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353977/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">Fig. 16C</figureCitation>
). Orbit distinct, eye small, slightly movable, cornea pigmented (
<figureCitation box="[1339,1439,975,999]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="21.[136,171,2062,2084]" captionTargetBox="[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetId="figure-40@21.[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Fig. 16. Hexapinus latus, new species, holotype female (8.1 × 5.0 mm) (MZB Cru 3918). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353977/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">Fig. 16C</figureCitation>
). Pterygostomial region with row of oblique striae. Third maxillipeds relatively broad (
<figureCitation box="[1132,1242,1039,1063]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="21.[136,171,2062,2084]" captionTargetBox="[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetId="figure-40@21.[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Fig. 16. Hexapinus latus, new species, holotype female (8.1 × 5.0 mm) (MZB Cru 3918). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353977/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">Figs. 16B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1255,1302,1039,1063]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="22.[113,148,786,808]" captionTargetBox="[117,1443,190,740]" captionTargetId="figure-11@22.[89,1463,174,758]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="Fig. 17. Hexapinus latus, new species, holotype female (8.1 × 5.0 mm) (MZB). A, dorsal view of carapace; B, left third maxilliped; C, abdomen and telson. Scale bars: A, C = 1.0 mm; B = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353979/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">17B</figureCitation>
); ischium 1.1 times as broad as long, longer than merus, strongly expanded distomesially, with rounded mesial margin; combined length of dactylus, propodus and carpus shorter than that of merus and ischium; exopod narrow, about 0.3 times width of ischium, flagellum well developed. Chelipeds stout, unequal (
<figureCitation box="[820,921,1231,1255]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="21.[136,171,2062,2084]" captionTargetBox="[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetId="figure-40@21.[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Fig. 16. Hexapinus latus, new species, holotype female (8.1 × 5.0 mm) (MZB Cru 3918). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353977/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">Fig. 16C</figureCitation>
); major chela gaping when fingers closed; palm slightly wider than long, outer surface smooth, tubercles on upper margin; minor chela with narrower gap between closed fingers (
<figureCitation box="[898,995,1327,1351]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="21.[136,171,2062,2084]" captionTargetBox="[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetId="figure-40@21.[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Fig. 16. Hexapinus latus, new species, holotype female (8.1 × 5.0 mm) (MZB Cru 3918). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353977/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">Fig. 16C</figureCitation>
). P2–P4 (
<figureCitation box="[1095,1191,1327,1351]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="21.[136,171,2062,2084]" captionTargetBox="[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetId="figure-40@21.[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Fig. 16. Hexapinus latus, new species, holotype female (8.1 × 5.0 mm) (MZB Cru 3918). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353977/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">Fig. 16A</figureCitation>
) short, stout, P3 longest; merus of P4 about 2 times as long as broad; dactylus longer than propodus; dactylus of P4 slightly upcurved. Female thoracic sternum broad (
<figureCitation box="[1075,1183,1423,1447]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="21.[136,171,2062,2084]" captionTargetBox="[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetId="figure-40@21.[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Fig. 16. Hexapinus latus, new species, holotype female (8.1 × 5.0 mm) (MZB Cru 3918). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353977/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">Figs. 16B</figureCitation>
), sternites 1 and 2 fused, separated from sternite 3 by distinct ridge; sternite 3 separated from sternite 4 by distinct ridge. Female abdomen broad (
<figureCitation box="[820,924,1519,1543]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="21.[136,171,2062,2084]" captionTargetBox="[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetId="figure-40@21.[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Fig. 16. Hexapinus latus, new species, holotype female (8.1 × 5.0 mm) (MZB Cru 3918). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353977/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">Figs. 16B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[934,979,1519,1543]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="22.[113,148,786,808]" captionTargetBox="[117,1443,190,740]" captionTargetId="figure-11@22.[89,1463,174,758]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="Fig. 17. Hexapinus latus, new species, holotype female (8.1 × 5.0 mm) (MZB). A, dorsal view of carapace; B, left third maxilliped; C, abdomen and telson. Scale bars: A, C = 1.0 mm; B = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353979/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">17C</figureCitation>
) with 6 free somites and subtriangular telson.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[812,1451,1582,1639]" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[812,896,1582,1606]" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">Colour.</emphasis>
In life, the carapace and appendages are creamishwhite overall.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="416" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="20.[812,1451,1679,1735]" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[812,940,1679,1703]" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Latin 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[1125,1177,1679,1703]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="20" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latus">
<emphasis box="[1125,1177,1679,1703]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">latus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for broad/wide, alluding to the broad carapace.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="418" pageId="20" pageNumber="416" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="20.[812,1452,1775,2119]" lastBlockId="22.[113,753,892,1108]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="418" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[812,923,1775,1799]" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">Remarks.</emphasis>
Although only female specimens were available, this species clearly belongs to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Manning &amp; Holthuis" authorityYear="1981" box="[1148,1262,1807,1830]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="20" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1148,1262,1807,1830]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">Hexapinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as it has a broad and mesially convex ischium of the third maxilliped, and the P2–P4 are short. The broad carapace of 
<taxonomicName authority="Rahayu &amp; Ng, 2014" authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[1303,1391,1871,1895]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="20" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latus" status="new species">
<emphasis box="[1303,1391,1871,1895]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">H. latus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="20" pageNumber="416" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
, is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Rahayu &amp; Ng, 2014" authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[1056,1175,1903,1927]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="20" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simplex" status="new species">
<emphasis box="[1056,1175,1903,1927]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">H. simplex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1193,1332,1903,1927]" pageId="20" pageNumber="416" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
. However, comparisons of similar-sized females show that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[1325,1409,1935,1959]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="20" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latus">
<emphasis box="[1325,1409,1935,1959]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">H. latus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a proportionately broader abdomen with the telson as long as somite 6 (
<figureCitation box="[952,1049,1999,2023]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="22.[113,148,786,808]" captionTargetBox="[117,1443,190,740]" captionTargetId="figure-11@22.[89,1463,174,758]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="Fig. 17. Hexapinus latus, new species, holotype female (8.1 × 5.0 mm) (MZB). A, dorsal view of carapace; B, left third maxilliped; C, abdomen and telson. Scale bars: A, C = 1.0 mm; B = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353979/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">Fig. 17C</figureCitation>
) while in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[1162,1277,1999,2023]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="20" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis box="[1162,1277,1999,2023]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">H. simplex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the abdomen is narrow and the telson is shorter than the sixth abdominal somite (
<figureCitation box="[908,1018,2063,2087]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="26.[113,148,2033,2055]" captionTargetBox="[120,1452,1048,1993]" captionTargetId="figure-11@26.[110,1469,1012,2019]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="Fig. 21. Hexapinus simplex, new species. A, B, F, holotype male (7.8 × 5.0 mm) (MZB); C, paratype female (6.9 × 4.5 mm) (ZRC 2013.1689); D, paratype female (4.5 × 2.8 mm) (ZRC 2013.1689); E, paratype male (5.4 × 3.4 mm) (ZRC 2013.1689); G, male (12.7 × 7.5 mm)(ZRC 2012.1016). A, B, G1; C, D, female abdomen and telson; E–G, male abdomen and telson. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353989" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353989/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">Fig. 21D</figureCitation>
). In addition, the merus of the third maxilliped of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[960,1044,2095,2119]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="20" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latus">
<emphasis box="[960,1044,2095,2119]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">H. latus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is shorter than the ischium (
<figureCitation box="[1342,1438,2095,2119]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="22.[113,148,786,808]" captionTargetBox="[117,1443,190,740]" captionTargetId="figure-11@22.[89,1463,174,758]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="Fig. 17. Hexapinus latus, new species, holotype female (8.1 × 5.0 mm) (MZB). A, dorsal view of carapace; B, left third maxilliped; C, abdomen and telson. Scale bars: A, C = 1.0 mm; B = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353979/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="416">Fig. 17B</figureCitation>
), while in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[213,330,892,916]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis box="[213,330,892,916]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">H. simplex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the merus is longer than the ischium (
<figureCitation box="[121,227,924,948]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="25.[137,172,2033,2055]" captionTargetBox="[122,1470,374,1991]" captionTargetId="figure-7@25.[122,1480,366,2014]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="Fig. 20. Hexapinus simplex, new species, holotype male (7.8 × 5.0 mm) (MZB Cru 3791). A, carapace; B, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing thoracic sternal groove; C, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing thoracic sternal groove and telson; D, anterior view of cephalothorax; E, major chela; F, minor chela; G, left third maxilliped. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353985" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353985/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">Fig. 20G</figureCitation>
). The posterolateral margin of the carapace of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[113,200,956,980]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latus">
<emphasis box="[113,200,956,980]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">H. latus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has only one protuberance (
<figureCitation box="[513,612,956,980]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="21.[136,171,2062,2084]" captionTargetBox="[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetId="figure-40@21.[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Fig. 16. Hexapinus latus, new species, holotype female (8.1 × 5.0 mm) (MZB Cru 3918). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353977/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">Fig. 16A</figureCitation>
) while in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">H. simplex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it always has two protuberances (
<figureCitation box="[585,688,988,1012]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="23.[136,171,2059,2081]" captionTargetBox="[159,1449,187,2035]" captionTargetId="figure-45@23.[159,1449,187,2035]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="Fig. 18. Hexapinus simplex, new species. A, B, holotype male (7.8 × 5.0 mm) (MZB Cru 3790); C, paratype female (6.9 × 4.5 mm) (MZB 3791). A, C, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, carapace." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353981" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353981/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">Fig. 18B</figureCitation>
). The dorsal carapace surface of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[420,510,1020,1044]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latus">
<emphasis box="[420,510,1020,1044]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">H. latus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very smooth (
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="21.[136,171,2062,2084]" captionTargetBox="[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetId="figure-40@21.[138,1476,333,2029]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Fig. 16. Hexapinus latus, new species, holotype female (8.1 × 5.0 mm) (MZB Cru 3918). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353977/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">Fig. 16A</figureCitation>
); specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[337,453,1052,1076]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis box="[337,453,1052,1076]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">H. simplex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the size of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[587,674,1052,1076]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latus">
<emphasis box="[587,674,1052,1076]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">H. latus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the other hand, are always distinctively pitted (
<figureCitation box="[586,667,1084,1108]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="23.[136,171,2059,2081]" captionTargetBox="[159,1449,187,2035]" captionTargetId="figure-45@23.[159,1449,187,2035]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="Fig. 18. Hexapinus simplex, new species. A, B, holotype male (7.8 × 5.0 mm) (MZB Cru 3790); C, paratype female (6.9 × 4.5 mm) (MZB 3791). A, C, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, carapace." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353981" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353981/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353977" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5353977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353977/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="417" startId="21.[136,171,2062,2084]" targetBox="[138,1476,333,2029]" targetPageId="21">
<paragraph blockId="21.[136,1475,2062,2113]" pageId="21" pageNumber="417">
Fig. 16. 
<taxonomicName authority="Rahayu &amp; Ng, 2014" authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[222,382,2062,2083]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="21" pageNumber="417" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latus" status="new species">
<emphasis box="[222,382,2062,2083]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="417">Hexapinus latus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[397,518,2062,2084]" pageId="21" pageNumber="417" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
, holotype female (8.1 × 5.0 mm) (MZB Cru 3918). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353979" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5353979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353979/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" startId="22.[113,148,786,808]" targetBox="[117,1443,190,740]" targetPageId="22">
<paragraph blockId="22.[113,1451,786,837]" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">
Fig. 17. 
<taxonomicName authority="Rahayu &amp; Ng, 2014" authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[198,356,786,808]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latus" status="new species">
<emphasis box="[198,356,786,808]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">Hexapinus latus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[370,490,786,808]" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
, holotype female (8.1 × 5.0 mm) (MZB). A, dorsal view of carapace; B, left third maxilliped; C, abdomen and telson. Scale bars: A, C = 1.0 mm; B = 0.5 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="22.[113,753,1148,1428]" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">
Although 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[225,313,1148,1172]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latus">
<emphasis box="[225,313,1148,1172]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">H. latus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected in the same island as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">H. simplex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the differences discussed above argue against them being conspecific. The habitats of also appear to be somewhat different. The specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[430,520,1244,1268]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latus">
<emphasis box="[430,520,1244,1268]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">H. latus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were collected from coarse white sand in shallow depressions in the reef flat. The area had previously been mined for building material by local villagers. The area is always filled with some water, even during low tide. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[351,554,1372,1396]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis box="[351,554,1372,1396]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">Hexapinus simplex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the other hand seems to prefer finer substrates (see next species).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[113,753,1468,1812]" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[113,286,1468,1492]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latus">
<emphasis box="[113,286,1468,1492]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">Hexapinus latus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="De Haan" baseAuthorityYear="1835" box="[475,579,1468,1492]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latipes">
<emphasis box="[475,579,1468,1492]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">H. latipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having broad female abdomen. In a female specimen of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="De Haan" baseAuthorityYear="1835" box="[582,688,1500,1524]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latipes">
<emphasis box="[582,688,1500,1524]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">H. latipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(10.2 × 
<quantity box="[139,226,1532,1556]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.6" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" unit="mm" value="7.6">7.6 mm</quantity>
, NSMT-Cr 5694), which is slightly larger than the female 
<typeStatus box="[235,281,1565,1589]" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">type</typeStatus>
specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[439,525,1564,1588]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latus">
<emphasis box="[439,525,1564,1588]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">H. latus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the abdomen is still narrow and resembles that of a male (
<figureCitation box="[528,625,1596,1620]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="22.[113,148,786,808]" captionTargetBox="[117,1443,190,740]" captionTargetId="figure-11@22.[89,1463,174,758]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="Fig. 17. Hexapinus latus, new species, holotype female (8.1 × 5.0 mm) (MZB). A, dorsal view of carapace; B, left third maxilliped; C, abdomen and telson. Scale bars: A, C = 1.0 mm; B = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353979/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">Fig. 17C</figureCitation>
versus 
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="17.[137,172,2006,2028]" captionTargetBox="[143,1475,391,1968]" captionTargetId="figure-7@17.[91,1489,371,1985]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Fig. 13. Hexapinus latipes (De Haan, 1835). A, B, E, G, female (10.2 × 7.6 mm) (NSMT-Cr 5694); C, holotype female (10.6 × 6.4 mm) (RMNH 31783d; D, F, female (30.4 × 17.5 mm) (KPM NH 6331). A, overall view of carapace; B, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing thoracic sternal groove and sternoabdominal cavity; C–E, left third maxilliped; F, G, female abdomen and telson. Scale bars: A, B, D–G = 1.0 mm; C not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353971" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353971/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">Fig. 13G</figureCitation>
). The female abdomens of both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[515,601,1628,1652]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latus">
<emphasis box="[515,601,1628,1652]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">H. latus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[656,745,1629,1652]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ceres">
<emphasis box="[656,745,1629,1652]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">H. ceres</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, even though they are relatively small, are already broad. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[113,289,1692,1716]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latus">
<emphasis box="[113,289,1692,1716]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">Hexapinus latus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[346,437,1693,1716]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ceres">
<emphasis box="[346,437,1693,1716]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">H. ceres</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are easily distinguished; the carapace surface, chelipeds and P2–P4 of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[549,631,1724,1748]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latus">
<emphasis box="[549,631,1724,1748]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">H. latus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are smooth (
<figureCitation box="[121,221,1756,1780]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="22.[113,148,786,808]" captionTargetBox="[117,1443,190,740]" captionTargetId="figure-11@22.[89,1463,174,758]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="Fig. 17. Hexapinus latus, new species, holotype female (8.1 × 5.0 mm) (MZB). A, dorsal view of carapace; B, left third maxilliped; C, abdomen and telson. Scale bars: A, C = 1.0 mm; B = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353979/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">Fig. 17A</figureCitation>
) but in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[312,403,1757,1780]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ceres">
<emphasis box="[312,403,1757,1780]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">H. ceres</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, these are covered with closely spaced granules (
<figureCitation box="[302,403,1788,1812]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="19.[136,171,2063,2085]" captionTargetBox="[136,1474,723,2032]" captionTargetId="figure-278@19.[136,1474,723,2032]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Fig. 14. Hexapinus ceres, new species, holotype female (5.5 × 3.3 mm) (NMCR 39070). A, overall view of carapace, left cheliped and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax; D, abdomen and telson." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353973" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353973/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="418">Fig. 14A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
